# Keeping rules up to date

When you modify code in an area covered by a `.cursor/rules/` file, update that file in the same change if the modification makes any rule stale or incomplete. The mapping:

| If you touch…                                        | Update…           |
| ---------------------------------------------------- | ----------------- |
| `src/components/**`                                  | `components.mdc`  |
| `src/store/**`                                       | `store.mdc`       |
| `src/types/graph.ts`, `src/data/edgeTypes.ts`        | `graph-model.mdc` |
| `src/components/MentorBubble.tsx`, AI provider/model | `mentor.mdc`      |
| Coding patterns, naming, import conventions          | `conventions.mdc` |
| Architectural constraints, "never do X" rules        | `constraints.mdc` |
| `CHANGELOG.md`                                       | `changelog.mdc`   |
| Overall stack, layout, core concepts                 | `project.mdc`     |

## README roadmap (`## Roadmap`)

When you **complete** work that satisfies an unchecked item under `## Roadmap` in `README.md`, update that line to `- [x] ...` in the **same commit or PR** as the implementation.

- If you ship something that clearly matches an existing roadmap line but wording drifted, adjust the line text so it still describes what shipped, then check it off.
- If you add a significant **new** user-facing capability that belongs on the public roadmap, add a matching `- [ ]` line (keep items one line, consistent with the existing list).
- If plans change and an item is dropped or replaced, edit or remove that line so the roadmap stays honest — do not leave stale `[ ]` rows for cancelled work without a brief reason or replacement.
